	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <span id= >Anonymous</span><br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Default [2.00]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>Those are stat points at creation.&nbsp;&nbsp;I assume the person asking about skill points meant the skill points you get every level at the guild trainer.<br><br>I recommend putting your first points as a newbie into piercing, to help you win those first few fights where your dagger is doing most of the damage to some level 1 mob.<br><br>Your spell skills will get maxxed automatically, except evocation.  Practice it by casting ward undead on your pet.<br><br>One place to put a few points quite soon is tailoring if you're a DE or gnome who's not too twinked to loot.  If you get a tailor kit, you can make spiderling silks into threads that sell well to players making armor for looks, or practicing to make 10-slot backpacks.  Spider silks can be made into stackable swatches.  Otherwise they fill your inventory rather quickly.  It's also convenient to be able to make raw silk armor if you want to start a caster char out with a set of something, because the silk swatches don't take up much bank space, whereas storing a whole set of newbie gear for your next alt will fill your bank very quickly.<br><br>Later on, the main use of your training points will be research.</p>&nbsp;<br> </td></td></tr>
